WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.040
Hello everyone, welcome to an exciting talk.

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:19.480
So today we'll be discussing about this talk, which is When Rivers Speak, Analyzing Massive

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:24.160
Water Quality Datasets Using SSH in Positron.

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:32.880
So Roger Gers is a Cure A engineer at Poseidon, so stay tuned and follow this exciting talk.

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:39.200
Thank you.

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:40.200
Thank you very much.

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:41.200
Yeah.

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:47.680
And yeah, so my talk today is When Rivers Speak, Analyzing Massive Water Quality Datasets Using

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:49.680
Remote SSH in Positron.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:51.320
My name is Rodrigo.

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:55.840
A little bit about myself, just to start with.

00:00:55.840 --> 00:01:00.520
I'm a Cure Engineer at Posit, and I'm originally from Salvador, Brazil.

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:02.439
That's my city, by the way.

00:01:02.439 --> 00:01:04.320
But I'm based in Pittsburgh.

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:09.000
My background is actually in chemistry, so it's very exciting actually to be at PyData

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.320
Boston with the Python community, because then I can get to learn a lot from the different

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:17.000
talks and so on from everyone.

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:22.360
My main interests lie at the intersection of statistics, data, and society, especially

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:28.360
with how to use data and statistics to understand and improve the world.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:33.800
That's the overarching theme of many of my talks, and that's related to what I'll be

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:36.519
presenting today.

00:01:36.519 --> 00:01:40.480
Throughout the talk, if anyone has any questions, please feel free to interrupt.

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:42.680
I really don't mind.

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:46.559
So yeah.

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:52.519
So just an overview of the presentation, I'll start by talking about rivers as storytellers

00:01:52.519 --> 00:01:54.160
of human history.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:02:00.440
Then I'll dive more into the U.S. Geological Survey sensor network.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:06.599
And then we'll talk more about the technical aspects of how to take advantage of all those

00:02:06.599 --> 00:02:12.759
massive pieces of data that are available through APIs.

00:02:12.759 --> 00:02:18.240
And then we'll talk more about remote station positron as a potential solution to enable

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:22.240
capturing and making sense of all of this data.

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:26.600
And then in conclusion, I'll just wrap up with how data science can be a tool for a

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:29.619
better world.

00:02:29.619 --> 00:02:37.000
So beginning with rivers as storytellers, that's something that I became very interested

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:43.919
in as a chemist, who is also interested in the statistics part of things.

00:02:43.919 --> 00:02:51.279
So this is a map of the U.S. with all rivers that someone used open source data from the

00:02:51.279 --> 00:03:00.160
National Hydrography Dataset in order to capture all of this.

00:03:00.160 --> 00:03:06.960
And in terms of rivers, what really makes me very fascinated about them is their ability

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:14.720
to record several dimensions of human history from migration patterns to industrialization,

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:20.919
ecological resilience, inequality, neglect, and environmental deregulation or regulation

00:03:20.919 --> 00:03:21.919
and so on.

00:03:21.919 --> 00:03:27.520
So just as an example, that's a historical map of the Delaware River showcasing the route

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:30.800
that George Washington's troops went through.

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:39.919
So that idea of rivers as storytellers of societies and of human history has always

00:03:39.919 --> 00:03:41.279
interested me.

00:03:41.279 --> 00:03:46.399
And that's part of the reason why I decided to talk about this today.

00:03:46.399 --> 00:03:52.520
And more particularly, along with that theme of rivers as storytellers, I was always fascinated

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:59.479
by the amount of data that's produced, especially here in the United States, from these rivers.

00:03:59.479 --> 00:04:05.839
I live in Pittsburgh, and Pittsburgh has essentially the beginning of the Ohio River.

00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:10.720
There are two rivers, the Alangany and the Monongahela River, that get together, forming

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:12.639
the Ohio River.

00:04:12.639 --> 00:04:17.220
And the Ohio River has actually been used for a lot of mathematical modeling in terms

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:22.820
of like pollution and patterns of rivers, just because of the pollution that goes into

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:24.339
it, unfortunately.

00:04:24.339 --> 00:04:31.260
So that's what I was interested as well, about the idea of capturing that data from

00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:38.739
U.S. Geological Survey in order to try to understand patterns of those rivers.

00:04:38.739 --> 00:04:46.140
And in terms of the size of that network, the United States has one of the largest environmental

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:54.980
monitoring systems in the world, with over 2.3 million sites spread all over the country.

00:04:54.980 --> 00:05:01.059
And many of those sites are capturing data every 15 minutes.

00:05:01.059 --> 00:05:05.920
The one they station at the beginning of the Ohio River, for example, it captures a bunch

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:08.859
of water quality parameters every 15 minutes.

00:05:08.859 --> 00:05:15.980
And there is an API streaming that data as we speak, leading to hundreds of millions

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:21.839
of measurements, as well as several years of data.

00:05:21.839 --> 00:05:27.059
Some of the more recent data is more complete.

00:05:27.059 --> 00:05:37.700
However, even in the past, there has been some data being streamed from those stations.

00:05:37.700 --> 00:05:39.100
Which leads to two questions.

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:42.940
Why should we care about river data?

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:51.260
As well as how can we listen to these massive amounts of data that rivers have been sharing?

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:58.859
And to answer the first question, I think water quality data reveals a lot of things

00:05:58.859 --> 00:06:05.579
that are of societal concern, including shifts in regulation, political priorities, economic

00:06:05.579 --> 00:06:11.619
development, environmental justice, and climate transformations, in a way that data is not

00:06:11.619 --> 00:06:19.260
just numbers, but the social history that encodes a lot of aspects of our societies.

00:06:19.260 --> 00:06:23.220
So that's why I became more and more interested in that.

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:32.299
And in terms of how can we listen to the data that rivers are sharing, that is a challenge.

00:06:32.299 --> 00:06:38.579
Because both in terms of computation, as well as storage, and so on, it's difficult

00:06:38.579 --> 00:06:46.579
to be able to capture the magnitude of that data and to be able to process it and analyze

00:06:46.579 --> 00:06:47.859
it and so on.

00:06:47.859 --> 00:06:53.739
So that's what made me really intrigued by that problem.

00:06:53.739 --> 00:06:58.220
Which leads to us talking about the technical overview of what we'll do today.

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:05.100
So the first step was to fetch the national data, a national site index.

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:12.220
That national site index contains the number that's assigned for each of those sites that

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:14.739
are spread all over the United States.

00:07:14.739 --> 00:07:20.619
And the reason why we have to be very strategic about how to fetch is because those numbers

00:07:20.619 --> 00:07:24.779
are together with a massive amount of data.

00:07:24.779 --> 00:07:28.940
And a lot of those APIs are quite old.

00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:34.559
So it's difficult to be able to process all of that and to have a correlation between

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:36.899
each number and each site.

00:07:36.899 --> 00:07:42.739
And there's no very accessible way to see here's a list of all numbers and all sites.

00:07:42.739 --> 00:07:49.739
You really have to make API calls and so on to the USGS water services API.

00:07:49.739 --> 00:07:57.579
And then we'll go through the sink ingestion of three years of data.

00:07:57.579 --> 00:08:02.299
We are only doing three years because just three years is already massive.

00:08:02.299 --> 00:08:06.640
We could go to 30 years of data and see what happens.

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:14.260
One caveat though is that some of the data for some stations only became available recently.

00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:16.019
So that's the tricky part.

00:08:16.019 --> 00:08:21.820
So there could be a high level of missingness in some stations and so on.

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:27.820
So that's what the third topic is, scaling to 30 years.

00:08:27.820 --> 00:08:33.940
And then followed by structuring the big data with Parquet or DuckDB.

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:39.219
And then finally interpreting environmental time series as a sociological and historical

00:08:39.219 --> 00:08:43.780
evidence.

00:08:43.780 --> 00:08:46.340
Any questions so far that anyone has?

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:47.340
Yeah, go ahead.

00:08:47.340 --> 00:08:48.340
Where does this data live?

00:08:48.340 --> 00:08:54.619
Do you need to continuously record it or is it there's some government servers you need

00:08:54.619 --> 00:08:55.619
to find?

00:08:55.619 --> 00:08:56.619
Yeah.

00:08:56.619 --> 00:08:59.700
So the question was where the data lives.

00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:07.179
So there's the USGS API water services API that you can make calls to.

00:09:07.179 --> 00:09:13.700
And that data is being in a lot of stations it's being streamed every 15 minutes for example.

00:09:14.619 --> 00:09:20.419
If anyone wants to explore more of this data, just a heads up that I think in January 2026

00:09:20.419 --> 00:09:29.299
a lot of the API endpoints are being deprecated, which makes that whole idea of exploring those

00:09:29.299 --> 00:09:34.859
data sets extremely relevant and pressing in terms of time.

00:09:34.859 --> 00:09:39.299
And it's easy to assume that someone out there is doing it.

00:09:39.299 --> 00:09:40.940
And I hope so.

00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:50.940
But just in case I've saved parts of the data set in my machine.

00:09:50.940 --> 00:09:57.219
So in terms, so the first part about fetching the national site index, there is a large

00:09:57.219 --> 00:10:02.619
inventory of more than 1.7 million rows after processing.

00:10:02.619 --> 00:10:08.260
And then doing some cleaning, the duplication and filtering of the stream sites, which results

00:10:08.340 --> 00:10:15.020
in the master table for the, that helps with the downstream workflow.

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:17.340
I can show this part later.

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:24.739
I think that would be easier so that we don't have to switch between applications now.

00:10:24.739 --> 00:10:34.780
But the idea is to use those values as part of the national site indexes as parameters

00:10:34.780 --> 00:10:42.419
to make the API calls to the four different water quality parameters that I'm interested

00:10:42.419 --> 00:10:44.380
in.

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:52.219
And those four different water quality parameters are listed here in this table, temperature,

00:10:52.219 --> 00:10:56.700
specific conductance, dissolved oxygen and pH.

00:10:56.700 --> 00:11:03.539
And each of them I find interesting because they reveal patterns around pollution, industrial

00:11:03.539 --> 00:11:07.940
activity, weather and so on.

00:11:07.940 --> 00:11:14.340
And all of this is very important for the wildlife that lives in the river and in the

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:18.380
surrounding areas of the river as well.

00:11:18.380 --> 00:11:21.780
And for us as well, we are also part of nature.

00:11:21.780 --> 00:11:29.260
So that's actually important to have, to monitor those parameters and so on.

00:11:29.260 --> 00:11:34.380
This is a caveat though, there are a bunch of other parameters and some of them are actually

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:40.260
very important to prevent or to plan for flooding.

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:44.820
For example, there are some rivers in the US where there's flooding in the surrounding

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:46.640
regions from time to time.

00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:54.299
So they do have parameters related to the height of the river and so on.

00:11:54.340 --> 00:12:00.859
So in terms of temperature, very high values can stress the aquatic life, very low values

00:12:00.859 --> 00:12:05.940
can slow the metabolism of the organisms living there.

00:12:05.940 --> 00:12:14.140
The specific conductance is typically correlated with clean or polluted water.

00:12:14.140 --> 00:12:18.020
Low values would indicate that typically the water is clean.

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:24.619
High values could indicate some pollution from industry and so on.

00:12:24.619 --> 00:12:30.419
Dissolved oxygen is one of the main ways also to quantify pollution because if you have

00:12:30.419 --> 00:12:36.619
very low dissolved oxygen, it usually indicates that zones and fish kills, whereas high dissolved

00:12:36.619 --> 00:12:39.979
oxygen usually indicates a healthy ecosystem.

00:12:39.979 --> 00:12:47.700
And finally the pH can indicate possible contamination or mineral imbalance in the water, which can

00:12:47.700 --> 00:13:00.340
cause some stress to the species and so on.

00:13:00.340 --> 00:13:10.400
So then in terms of the ingestion of those four parameters, there are thousands of sites

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:12.419
for each state.

00:13:12.419 --> 00:13:18.979
Some cities might have even multiple sites where data is being collected, and leading

00:13:18.979 --> 00:13:22.659
to millions of rows per ingestion batch.

00:13:22.659 --> 00:13:28.780
And by ingestion batch here, I mean that in the way I plan the ingestion, I decided to

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:31.419
do it by state.

00:13:31.419 --> 00:13:38.940
And then using a sync request and thread post to speed up the process is also helpful, which

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:43.260
leads to producing the state-level Parquet partitions.

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:50.219
And in the end, just three years of data, four parameters, leads to 1.8 gigabytes of

00:13:50.219 --> 00:13:51.219
Parquet data.

00:13:51.219 --> 00:13:54.380
If you do it in CSV instead, it's much larger.

00:13:54.380 --> 00:14:00.780
If you decide to collect the other parameters, it would also increase massively, along with

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:06.380
expanding the year window would also lead to massive expansion.

00:14:06.539 --> 00:14:13.940
I will show that data after in the positron application.

00:14:13.940 --> 00:14:21.700
And then I was thinking, just as a planning for potential future exploration, what would

00:14:21.700 --> 00:14:32.659
be like to scale for 30 years of data if there was a feasible way to outgrow laptops' limitations.

00:14:32.700 --> 00:14:39.979
The reason why I say that is because although many of us do have machines that can process

00:14:39.979 --> 00:14:46.979
a lot of data and can collect at scale and so on, sometimes if you have limitations in

00:14:46.979 --> 00:14:54.539
terms of equipment, in terms of computing capacity, even tasks that we are used to in

00:14:54.539 --> 00:14:58.539
terms of data collection and processing can be a challenge.

00:14:59.539 --> 00:15:08.179
Even for three years of data, collecting the data without just with my machine, for example,

00:15:08.179 --> 00:15:13.140
it took about 70 minutes of running it continuously.

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:17.900
And during that collection, there's always the ethical considerations behind it as well

00:15:17.900 --> 00:15:24.299
of making sure that you are not stressing servers, especially from government infrastructure

00:15:24.299 --> 00:15:25.500
and so on.

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:30.140
So all of this is very important to consider.

00:15:30.140 --> 00:15:36.380
And we have tens of millions of rows of sensor data if we were to go through 30 years, for

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:37.700
example.

00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:43.500
And if we scale up more than four parameters, that would also lead to several more columns.

00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:52.059
And I think there was someone who spoke earlier today about how columns really constitute

00:15:52.059 --> 00:15:57.260
a challenge for data processing capabilities and so on.

00:15:57.260 --> 00:16:04.739
And besides memory limits, some people can also be limited by storage.

00:16:04.739 --> 00:16:11.659
And that's how remote SSH can help overcome some of these gaps.

00:16:11.659 --> 00:16:14.179
Any questions up to this point?

00:16:14.179 --> 00:16:15.179
No?

00:16:15.179 --> 00:16:17.260
OK, cool.

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:26.619
So let's jump on to how remote SSH can be a solution to some of these challenges.

00:16:26.619 --> 00:16:32.919
So I'll start by explaining how it works in a higher level view.

00:16:32.919 --> 00:16:41.020
So in terms of compute and storage, there are different types of providers that can

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:47.739
provide virtual machines and so on so that we can remote into those virtual machines.

00:16:47.739 --> 00:16:53.460
If anyone, and in my talks, I always like to give ideas so that people can try it themselves

00:16:53.460 --> 00:16:54.460
for free.

00:16:54.460 --> 00:17:00.539
I usually don't like to, oh, let me recommend this provider or that provider.

00:17:00.539 --> 00:17:05.400
There are a bunch out there that are giving free trials and credits and so on.

00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:13.800
So if you want to try remote SSH with Positron and you need a VM or a provider, you can just

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:18.599
look it up for the ones that have free credits available.

00:17:18.599 --> 00:17:22.680
Some of them have very generous free trials.

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:26.000
So yeah, that can be a good option.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:34.319
And what remote SSH in Positron provides is a local UI with the ability to do remote computing.

00:17:34.319 --> 00:17:41.280
And that's very helpful because you're able to take advantage of Positron's capabilities

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:50.199
and the UI while outgrowing your computer's resources and so on.

00:17:50.199 --> 00:17:58.060
And what I find really good as well is to pair the expansion of computing capabilities

00:17:58.060 --> 00:18:05.939
with other good practices when it comes to large data sets, such as using Parquet files,

00:18:05.939 --> 00:18:11.380
for example, which are fully supported within the Data Explorer and so on, which I'll show

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:13.660
later as well.

00:18:13.660 --> 00:18:20.900
And lastly, that can help with a scalable network throughput for async ingestion pipelines,

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:23.619
which is what we have today.

00:18:23.619 --> 00:18:29.060
One caveat, though, is that, of course, when you are making API calls, there are limitations

00:18:29.060 --> 00:18:31.420
that are beyond your control.

00:18:31.420 --> 00:18:37.219
And you also don't want to stress external servers and so on.

00:18:37.219 --> 00:18:48.699
Yeah, so I already explained some of these reasons why to use remote SSH in Positron

00:18:48.699 --> 00:18:54.060
in terms of offloading some of the heavy data collection and processing work to a remote

00:18:54.060 --> 00:19:00.859
server, keeping the laptop responsive, having the workflow that data scientists usually

00:19:00.859 --> 00:19:10.000
like within Positron, and doing the long-running ingestion jobs and so on.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:16.579
And I think now it's a good time to actually show some of the UI and how these different

00:19:16.579 --> 00:19:25.859
factors are factored into the Positron's remote SSH.

00:19:25.859 --> 00:19:32.420
So with that, I put some screenshots of different areas of the application.

00:19:32.420 --> 00:19:39.459
The first one I would like to highlight here is that you can pre-configure specific hosts

00:19:39.459 --> 00:19:42.540
so that you can connect to the desired host.

00:19:42.540 --> 00:19:48.380
So once you click Connect to Host, there will be a list of your pre-configured hosts.

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:51.660
And then you can just go ahead and connect to it.

00:19:51.660 --> 00:19:57.939
This is very helpful if you have multiple remote environments, because sometimes people,

00:19:57.939 --> 00:20:06.420
for example, might set up one VM, one box for light tasks and another one for very heavy

00:20:06.420 --> 00:20:07.680
tasks.

00:20:07.680 --> 00:20:16.959
And since you're paying by the hour, you don't want necessarily to be using the wrong one

00:20:16.959 --> 00:20:21.319
for the wrong type of need that you have.

00:20:21.319 --> 00:20:31.239
So that's how you can connect to the host.

00:20:31.239 --> 00:20:35.760
Once you're connected, there is a very clear indication that you are connected in the lower

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:37.800
left corner.

00:20:37.800 --> 00:20:43.760
And I think that's very helpful to preventing anyone, including myself, from getting lost,

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:47.280
from not knowing which box you are at.

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:51.000
And I did play around with multiple boxes.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:58.439
And at some point, I had to rely on that indicator to know, oh, I'm still using that one.

00:20:58.439 --> 00:21:04.400
Let me swap to the next one, and so on.

00:21:04.400 --> 00:21:18.239
And then one other part that I find really helpful is the automated port forwarding,

00:21:18.239 --> 00:21:25.119
which means that you can have different types of applications and the hosts being forward

00:21:25.119 --> 00:21:27.239
to the specific ports.

00:21:27.239 --> 00:21:32.479
For me, that I'm not used to assigning the ports myself.

00:21:32.479 --> 00:21:36.040
That's just generally really helpful.

00:21:36.040 --> 00:21:39.959
You can run, as usual, the Shiny apps and so on.

00:21:39.959 --> 00:21:45.760
You can still run the Shiny app within Positron with the automated port forwarding, even when

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:52.439
you are inside a box.

00:21:52.439 --> 00:21:58.800
And lastly, there's the kernel supervisor, which is useful for very long running sessions,

00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:05.040
which means that you can shut down Positron, but still have the remote SSH running in the

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:09.119
background.

00:22:09.119 --> 00:22:14.099
Yeah.

00:22:14.099 --> 00:22:22.800
So with that, I'm gonna show a little bit about how the data looks like.

00:22:22.800 --> 00:22:24.800
For anyone who is curious.

00:22:24.800 --> 00:22:33.239
I did put on my GitHub as well.

00:22:33.239 --> 00:22:43.239
Okay.

00:22:43.239 --> 00:22:46.239
So let me show here.

00:22:46.239 --> 00:22:57.359
With your GitHub, can you get rid of the console?

00:22:57.359 --> 00:22:58.359
Yeah.

00:22:58.359 --> 00:22:59.359
I think...

