00:25:07.119 --> 00:25:13.500
And one thing I really like about exploring data with ThemePositor, and specifically with

00:25:13.500 --> 00:25:19.739
that data explorer tool, is the ability to interact with your data and get to know it

00:25:19.739 --> 00:25:21.339
better.

00:25:21.339 --> 00:25:28.020
Because especially now with AI, it's very easy to fall into the trap of asking AI to

00:25:28.020 --> 00:25:32.500
do things and then it messing things up.

00:25:32.500 --> 00:25:37.300
Whereas once you are actually interacting with the data, you get to know it better.

00:25:37.300 --> 00:25:38.939
And you can avoid some pitfalls.

00:25:38.939 --> 00:25:48.099
One example I would show here, for example, is if we go on to filter by parameter.

00:25:48.099 --> 00:25:49.260
So equal to...

00:25:49.260 --> 00:25:52.579
So I'm gonna put the pH parameter, okay?

00:25:52.579 --> 00:25:54.959
Which is 00400.

00:25:54.959 --> 00:25:57.420
And then I can apply the filter.

00:25:57.420 --> 00:26:01.660
And you can see here that it's quite fast.

00:26:01.979 --> 00:26:09.020
So it's 11% of my rows were for that parameter.

00:26:09.020 --> 00:26:14.300
And then one thing I had noted before already, but I just wanted to show, if you're interested

00:26:14.300 --> 00:26:22.020
about the data, everyone knows the range that pH is usually assigned to.

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:26.579
Like up to 14 and so on.

00:26:26.579 --> 00:26:34.859
If you go on sort ascending, for example, you can see that you have minus 99999.

00:26:34.859 --> 00:26:38.739
Does anyone know why that pH is so negative?

00:26:38.739 --> 00:26:40.859
Just like no data?

00:26:40.859 --> 00:26:41.859
Yeah.

00:26:41.859 --> 00:26:42.859
Yeah, just missing data.

00:26:42.859 --> 00:26:45.900
They just assigned that value.

00:26:45.900 --> 00:26:54.579
So yeah, situations like this, if you're not in close contact with your data, that's the

00:26:54.579 --> 00:27:03.300
type of thing that AI can take on and really hallucinate.

00:27:03.300 --> 00:27:10.619
And then let's say if you were to get the average, for example, of all of this, it would

00:27:10.619 --> 00:27:14.739
be quite bad because there is a lot...

00:27:14.739 --> 00:27:17.219
Like we can keep going.

00:27:17.219 --> 00:27:21.660
Like there's a lot of minus 9999 data.

00:27:21.739 --> 00:27:24.540
I mean, we can even like filter it.

00:27:24.540 --> 00:27:32.699
So let's say for value is equal to...

00:27:32.699 --> 00:27:34.660
Then apply the filter.

00:27:34.660 --> 00:27:39.660
So there are 11,600 rows of missing data.

00:27:39.660 --> 00:27:41.660
Is that applied?

00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:46.660
Because I can still filter to negative 999?

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:48.660
Oh, there's a different negative?

00:27:48.660 --> 00:27:50.660
Because I still have it.

00:27:51.660 --> 00:27:52.660
Filter to include.

00:27:52.660 --> 00:27:53.660
Oh, to include.

00:27:53.660 --> 00:27:54.660
Filter to include.

00:27:54.660 --> 00:27:55.660
Sorry.

00:27:55.660 --> 00:27:56.660
Sorry.

00:27:56.660 --> 00:27:57.660
Yeah.

