So in terms of the results of some exploration that I did for the three-year data collection,

00:30:52.859 --> 00:31:03.540
the ones in asterisk are ones that the speeds of the runtime were estimated, actually.

00:31:03.540 --> 00:31:06.660
I actually didn't do them.

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:14.339
But I tried to use a machine that performance is about the same as my laptop, as a baseline,

00:31:14.339 --> 00:31:24.219
as well as some stronger, like higher computing capabilities virtual machines.

00:31:24.219 --> 00:31:36.060
And I essentially did the same task and recorded how long it took for each of the remote hosts.

00:31:36.060 --> 00:31:41.859
And I could get up to this point of reducing from seven to one minutes, that's how long

00:31:41.859 --> 00:31:50.540
it took in my laptop, to 33 minutes, so by half, essentially, the time.

00:31:50.540 --> 00:31:54.099
Here are the costs, hourly cost, total cost per full run.

00:31:54.099 --> 00:31:59.459
Of course, usually you run into issues when you are doing it.

00:31:59.459 --> 00:32:02.819
Sometimes something might stop working and so on.

00:32:02.819 --> 00:32:10.619
So I wouldn't budget based on how long something would take to, you expect something to run.

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:14.540
But it's a good indicator, essentially.

00:32:14.540 --> 00:32:19.300
And the reason why I also stopped here is because once you start getting to a certain

00:32:19.300 --> 00:32:26.020
point, it doesn't really matter that much anymore what your computing capabilities are,

00:32:26.020 --> 00:32:31.859
because you might get rate-limited by the API and so on, and you don't want to stress

00:32:31.859 --> 00:32:34.020
the server or any of that.

00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:42.020
So it becomes less of a concern of your infrastructure that you're using, more of a concern of the

00:32:42.020 --> 00:32:49.300
external, the server infrastructure of the API provider.

00:32:49.300 --> 00:33:00.619
So yeah, and then in terms of when I think of processing 30 years of data, for example,

00:33:00.619 --> 00:33:06.300
I don't know what the results would look like, but it's very likely that that difference

00:33:06.300 --> 00:33:14.979
between my laptop versus more powerful machines would be very stark.

00:33:14.979 --> 00:33:22.900
The machines that I was using was from AWS, but there are a lot of virtual machine providers

00:33:22.900 --> 00:33:27.219
that can be good for that type of exploration.

